# Self-pin patterns for intent-eval-lab.
#
# Per iep-harness-hash-platform-rollout (bd_000-projects-g6zu) following the
# audit-harness@v1.1.0 self-pin pattern (PR #36 / bd_000-projects-itpl).
#
# The default audit-harness PATTERNS array targets generic consumer artifacts
# (.feature files, architecture configs, coverage thresholds) — none of which
# the lab uses. This file extends the pin scope to lab-specific load-bearing
# files: the CI workflows that enforce platform discipline, and the schema
# redirect stubs that anchor the kernel-canonical schema authority.
#
# Files NOT pinned (intentional):
#  - DRs and Blueprints — amended via formal governance (ISEDC), not by silent edit.
#  - Glossary, AARs, READMEs — frequent edits expected; pinning would create churn.
#  - 000-INDEX.md — updated on every doc add; same churn argument.
#
# Files PINNED below:

# CI workflow definitions — silent edits here are the silent-policy-erosion
# failure mode the harness exists to prevent (e.g., adding `|| true` to a grep
# that's supposed to block the PR).
.github/workflows/*.yml

# Evidence Bundle schema redirect stubs (per ISEDC Session 5 DR 018 § 6.4
# Option α-minus). These must stay redirect-stub-shaped; the schema-drift CI
# gate at .github/workflows/schema-drift.yml is the runtime check, and this
# hash pin is the integrity floor underneath it.
specs/evidence-bundle/v0.1.0-draft/schema/*.schema.json

# This extras file itself — bootstrap pin so a silent edit to the pin
# declarations can't subvert the mechanism. Matches audit-harness's own
# self-pin pattern (audit-harness/.harness-hash-extra-patterns line for
# `.harness-hash-extra-patterns`).
.harness-hash-extra-patterns

# The vendored audit-harness scripts + wrapper. Same rationale as
# audit-harness self-pinning its own scripts in PR #36 — these scripts ARE
# the policy enforcement surface. A silent edit to harness-hash.sh in the
# vendored copy could subvert the lab's hash check. Re-vendoring on a new
# audit-harness release requires a fresh `scripts/audit-harness init`.
.audit-harness/scripts/*.sh
.audit-harness/scripts/*.py
.audit-harness/bin/audit-harness.js
scripts/audit-harness

# The LLM-classifier deterministic walls (055-AT-SPEC). The autonomy policy,
# row schema, and earned-tier state are the enforcement surface for the
# classifier's one-hop autonomy gradient — a silent edit could flip a NEVER
# action (kernel_schema_edit, close_drift_signal) to allowed, or self-promote
# the earned tier. Pinning makes tier promotion structurally human: editing
# earned-tier.json requires a fresh `scripts/audit-harness init` in the same
# reviewed commit. (examples/ fixtures are intentionally NOT pinned — the
# self-test exercises them and churn is expected.)
specs/drift-classification/v1/*.json

# The walls script itself — same rationale as pinning the vendored
# audit-harness scripts above: it IS the policy enforcement surface.
scripts/classifier-walls.py

# The SAK Phase-4 advisory->blocking flip state machine + its schema. Same
# rationale as classifier-walls.py: these ARE the policy enforcement surface
# for the highest-blast-radius event in SAK (the advisory->blocking flip). A
# silent edit to the flip's hard-gate preconditions (zero-open-P0 + governance
# triple sign-off, plan 048 v8 Delta 3) or to the legal-transition graph could
# un-gate the flip. Pinning makes any change to the gate structurally reviewed:
# editing either file requires a fresh `scripts/audit-harness init` in the same
# commit. (DISTINCT from the 13-entity runtime state machine — that one is
# gated by statemachine-drift.yml, not the hash pin.)
scripts/sak-state-machine.py
specs/state-machines/schema/sak-state.schema.json
